Students taking this course are expected to better understand and explain regional development through European Regional Policy. By analyzing the origins, evolution and current operation of European regional Policy, students will be confronted with key issues regarding European integration, in particular its economic, institutional and decision making set up. They will also have the opportunity to explore the dilemmas facing the future of European regions i.e. enlargement, institutional reforms and the impacts of the single currency and the Single Market. Throughout the course, students will get acquainted with the role of the regions in the integration process and the related multi-level governance aspects.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course focuses on regional development and the role of the regions in the different stages of the European integration process. It looks more widely at economic and social cohesion as a central objective of the European Union and its wider implications for Europe as a whole. The course addresses four main aspects of the EU's regional policy: theoretical foundations and models of regional development; economic and social cohesion; regional policy at work; governance and regional implications of decentralization. In conclusion, the course will discuss the future of European regional policy and the challenges ahead in a globalized world.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon completion of this course students should:
- be able to frame disparities among Member states and identify their causes over time
- identify key objectives, actors, and policy instruments of the cohesion policy
- critically understand the origins of European regional policy
- be aware of the economic, institutional and political significance of regions in Europe today
- identify the new instruments of European regional policy and how they relate to globalization and accelerated technological change
